---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const blogContent = `
<p>As autonomous mathematical research systems scale, procedural orchestration becomes increasingly difficult to maintain and verify. Relying on complex <code>await</code> chains and nested loops introduces non-deterministic behavior that can compromise the integrity of the research pipeline.</p>

<p>To address these challenges, we transitioned Perqed's orchestration layer from a monolithic procedural implementation to a reactive state machine using <strong>XState v5</strong>. This architectural shift provides a formal framework for managing the research lifecycle—from literature-based ideation to empirical validation and formal verification.</p>

<h2>State Machine Topology</h2>

<p>The updated orchestration logic is represented as a Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) of state transitions. This approach ensures that the entire research process is deterministic and auditable. We have mapped the core research flow into a 10-state topology that explicitly handles successful transitions, falsification forks, and execution plateaus.</p>

<h2>Actor-Model Implementation</h2>

<p>Each component of the system—such as the <code>Librarian</code>, <code>Explorer</code>, and <code>Formalist</code>—is encapsulated as an isolated actor using XState's <code>fromPromise</code> API. These actors are stateless, receiving structured input and returning typed output, while the central Hub manages the transition logic.</p>

<p>This decoupling allows for robust error handling. For instance, if the <code>Validation</code> actor identifies an invalid syntax tree, the Hub captures the error, increments a retry counter, and re-routes the execution to the <code>Ideation</code> node. Similarly, if the <code>Explorer</code> identifies an energy plateau, the system can automatically transition to an SMT-based resolution node to evaluate the subspace using Z3.</p>

<h2>Verification and Testing</h2>

<p>The transition to a formal state machine has significantly improved our ability to verify the orchestration logic. By utilizing XState's <code>.provide()</code> API, we can inject mocked actors into the state machine, allowing for exhaustive testing of the topology without external dependencies.</p>

<p>Our validation suite verifies all 10 states and their associated transitions—including edge cases and terminal failure states—within a controlled environment. This ensures that the Hub-and-Spoke coordination remains consistent and resilient across diverse research tasks.</p>

<p>By implementing a mathematically sound orchestration layer, we have established a robust foundation for autonomous mathematical discovery.</p>
`;
---

<BaseLayout title="Reactive Math: Migrating Perqed to XState v5 — Perqed" activeNav="blog">

  <article class="article">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="prose">
        <header class="article-header">
          <div class="article-meta">
            <time>March 31, 2026</time>
            <span class="sep">·</span>
            <span>3 min read</span>
          </div>
          <h1>Reactive Math: Migrating Perqed's Core to XState v5</h1>
        </header>

        <div set:html={blogContent} />
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .article {
    padding: 64px 0 80px;
  }

  .article-header {
    margin-bottom: 40px;
  }

  .article-meta {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 8px;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }

  .sep {
    color: var(--text-muted);
  }

  .article :global(blockquote) {
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    padding-left: 16px;
    margin: 24px 0;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .article :global(table) {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    margin: 24px 0;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }

  .article :global(th) {
    text-align: left;
    font-weight: 600;
    padding: 10px 16px;
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--border-color);
    font-size: 0.84rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
  }

  .article :global(td) {
    padding: 10px 16px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
    vertical-align: top;
  }

  .article :global(tr:last-child td) {
    border-bottom: none;
  }

  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .article { padding: 32px 0 48px; }

    .article :global(table) {
      font-size: 0.8rem;
    }

    .article :global(th),
    .article :global(td) {
      padding: 8px 10px;
    }
  }
</style>
